{
  "texts": [
    "❹ Group Interests: As shown in Figure 5c, the group involvement of MBTI types points to distinct preferences.",
    "Ps are notably active in Myers-Briggs-related forums, while INTPs participate in groups focusing on intellectual debates like \"The Thinkers\" and \"The Scientists\".",
    "Js' involvement in \"find-friend\", although less pronounced, reflects a willingness to form connections beyond their intellectual interests.",
    "❺ Gender Difference: From Figure 5d, we observe some differences in MBTI traits across males and females.",
    "For instance, the INFJ and INFP personality types have a higher proportion of females, Historically, these traits have been more encouraged in males due to societal expectations that favor rationality and independence in men."
  ]
}